AGI - There was a sticker on his Fiat 500 yellow. A small, yet enormous symbol: a rifle broken by a pawn, emblem of the objectors of conscience. "I gave it to him," says Tiziana Palazzo, "because it perfectly represented what he believed in: the non-violence, justice, legality." &nbsp;Cominciates so, 40 years after his death, the story that makes the Agi the wife of Sergio Cosmai, director of the prison of Cosenza, murdered on March 12, 1985. He died the next day: he was 36 years old, left a wife, a three-year-old daughter, Rossella, and another incoming child. The 'ndrangheta decided that he had to die because with his work he had broken uncomfortable balances, had denied the bosses the privileges they considered due.> He did what was right to do. But it wasn't just the mob to condemn him: was institutional loneliness, the void around him, making it an even easier target.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
"Sergio was not a hero, he was a man of the state, an official who simply did his duty. Yet, in its normality, it was extraordinary: He respected everyone, from his collaborators to the prisoners. He never gave you, did not impose his role with authority, but with the example. He believed that within a prison the state should be present in every gesture, in every decision. Maybe that's what made him a uncomfortable man." &nbsp;
<br What happened on March 12th? &nbsp;>
"I didn't know anything, I didn't imagine. That day I was serene, I was expecting my husband to go and get our daughter to kindergarten. He had returned that morning from a mission to Vibo Valentia and brought me oranges, because he knew that in pregnancy I wanted it. A small, everyday, normal gesture. Then at two, he called: You have to go get the baby. “Yes, I go now,” he replied. After five minutes the machine with the killers waited around the corner." But she didn't know that yet. "I heard sirens in the distance, but I didn't even pass through my head that it could be for him. Then came the wife of a marshal, knocked, entered, turned out television. "I have to tell you something," he said. 'Your husband had an accident, but nothing serious'. He calmed me – he reconstructs Tiziana -, told me he was fine, that they would soon transfer him to a hospital in Bari. But I couldn't understand, I couldn't put the pieces together. The truth was kept hidden because I was pregnant, because they didn't want me to suffer a shock. And so I stayed there, suspended, in the void of an unreal wait, without knowing that my husband was already dead."
For years, the name of Sergio Cosmai has remained suspended.> His story, his sacrifice, were for too long an intimate, familiar, private memory. "In Bisceglie for a long time he didn't talk about him," says his wife. "I myself was immersed in a very complicated reality. Then, in 2005, everything changed: Some colleagues from my school said that it was not possible that in that high school, where they had studied the children of Sergio Cosmai and where I taught, no one would talk about it. From there the work of memory began”. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Justice has come even later than memory: for 27 years the name of Sergio Cosmai has been polluted in the forgotten phildons of an investigation that seemed destined to oblivion: "The first was called 'Missing', because the cards were gone. It was as if there had never been the will to find the leaders," says Tiziana Palace. Only in 2012 the envoy, Francesco Perna, was sentenced to life after the confirmation by the Cassation. But the material executors of the murder, although identified, were acquitted by lack of evidence. "It's an indecency, a shame," he says: "There is no judgment that can heal this wound."
To make everything even more painful was the climate of omerity in which the family was immersed. "I felt it on me, that silence. And I still feel it. There are too many people who preferred not to know, not to see. Even after his death, we felt alone. The Mafia is not only the one who kills, but also the silent, who turns on the other side”.&nbsp;
And who says that who is a victim of mafia, becomes a hero?&nbsp;>
"Sergio was not a hero, he was a man of the state, an official who simply did his duty," explains Tiziana. "He had brought dignity among those walls, had separated the bosses to prevent them from exercising their power even in prison, had denied oysters and champagne to those who wanted to live in luxury even behind bars. He just did his job. And for this reason he was killed.”&nbsp;
In the long chat there is also the son, the eponymous of his father, Sergio Cosmai. Why this choice? >
"It's no coincidence he's called Sergio Cosmai," says the lady. "But if I go back, I wouldn't make the same choice. Because today Sergio bears on his shoulders too heavy inheritance, a burden he did not deserve. When I chose it, it seemed like the right way to make it reborn, to keep it with us. But true rebirth is not a name: it is the recovery of memory, its history. This is the legacy we must leave." &nbsp;&nbsp; "I, growing up, met my father through the stories of others – adds his son, Sergio Cosmai -. It was a reverse path: I have no direct memories of him, but I feel a deep bond with his figure." &nbsp;<br> Today his name, after forty years, is no longer just the memory of those who loved him: it is a living memory. It's teaching. It's inheritance.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

